a:260:{i:0;a:1:{s:2:"id";s:19:"2391240582417624322";}i:1;a:1:{s:10:"short_code";s:11:"CEvZKPvgC0C";}i:2;a:1:{s:12:"created_time";i:1599278112;}i:3;a:1:{s:7:"caption";s:1957:"I feel like pestos have become the main part of my diet, trying to savor the fresh greens of summer still lurking around here in #Michigan , but also applying what Iâ€™m teaching myself. CoQ10 (ubiquinol/the ubiquitous quinone) is present in all plants & animals, yet considered low in plant diets. Broccoli is the highest plant source Iâ€™m aware of, & if you know #microgreens you know they are a brilliant method of getting all the nutrients of the larger final product in a tiny size, which means you can consume way more nutrients in a smaller portion. #superfoods 

Nettles have been a relatively new & exciting addition to my life, & Iâ€™ve been using a good bit of them from the garden. So hereâ€™s my adapted Nettle Pesto (from mine & Onyxâ€™s Little Koalas cookbook, DM to order) in case you want to try pesto with nettles, microgreens, or anything else! I used broccoli microgreens & Lea shoots in addition to the foraged #nettles here ğŸŒ± 

3 cups fresh stinging nettles
1 cup pea shoots (or more nettles)
1/2 cup micro broccoli
5-6 T olive oil
5 tbsp nutritional yeast
3 T lemon juice or 1-2 T vinegar
1 tsp dried thyme
1/2 tsp lemon zest
1/2 tsp salt
1/4 cup pumpkin seeds or pine nuts 
Water if needed to thin

Using gloves, carefully remove nettle leaves from stems. You can Blanch for 30 seconds if desired, but blending will remove sting. Add other ingredients except pumpkin seeds and pulse until broken down but still textured. Add pumpkin seeds and pulse until incorporated but still chunky. Store in fridge. Enjoy on toast, as a pizza topping, pasta, salad addition, or by the spoonful (my usual method)!

I also work with blendtec if you need a link to an amazing blender!

